---
import { useTranslations } from '../../lib/i18n';
const { lang = 'en' } = Astro.props;
const t = useTranslations(lang);
// No props needed

---
<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<!-- EXECUTIVE SUMMARY                           -->
<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<div class="mb-14 bg-gradient-to-b from-green-500/5 to-transparent border border-green-500/15 rounded-xl p-6">
  <h3 class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider text-green-400 mb-4">{t('ministrc.executive_summary.t1')}</h3>
  <div class="text-xs text-neutral-300 leading-relaxed space-y-3">
    <p>
      <strong class="text-white">The problem:</strong> STRC's coding sequence (5,325 bp) exceeds AAV packaging capacity (~4,400 bp) by 925 bp. The current approach splits the gene across two vectors, but mathematical modeling calibrated to published mouse data (Omichi 2020) predicts only ~27% efficiency in humans at clinical titers, a 2.8x penalty vs single-vector delivery.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong class="text-white">The hypothesis:</strong> AlphaFold 3 reveals that stereocilin's N-terminal half (residues 1-699) is intrinsically disordered (pTM 0.27, 38% unstructured), while the C-terminal half (700-1775) folds into a stable structure (pTM 0.87, 4% disordered). We propose removing the disordered N-terminal to create a truncated "mini-STRC" (3,228 bp) that fits in a single AAV vector with 1,472 bp of regulatory headroom.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong class="text-white">The evidence:</strong> 20 AF3 structure predictions, boundary sweep (4 cut points), and 8 independent web tools (SignalP, NetGPI, DeepLoc, NetNGlyc, IUPred3, PSIPRED, DISOPRED3, ESMFold) all converge on the same conclusion: the C-terminal half is the functional core. The IgK signal peptide scores 99.97% on SignalP 6.0 (vs 93.4% native). GPI-anchor signal intact. All 5 retained glycosylation sites functional. Cross-species conservation analysis across 9 mammals shows both halves are equally conserved (~92%), but the N-terminal is disordered despite this conservation, consistent with a structural spacer role rather than enzymatic function.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong class="text-white">The precedent:</strong> Micro-dystrophin used the same strategy (removing non-essential domains from an oversized gene) and received FDA approval in 2023 (Sarepta's SRP-9001).
    </p>
  </div>
</div>
